&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Creating the Foundation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We started by recovering recycled metal from abandoned mattresses. The springs were heated to straighten them and then cut using a plier. This metal was mixed with concrete to create our homemade weight plates.&lt;/p&gt;




&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Painting the Weights&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once the concrete dried, the plates were coated in matte black paint. At this stage, we finalized the 5kg weight plate design. However, we could only produce six at a time.&lt;/p&gt;






&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Our Finished Product&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The result: clean, consistent 5kg concrete weights reinforced with metal. A major milestone, but we werenâ€™t done yet.&lt;/p&gt;




&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Experimenting with Moulds&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To scale up, we began developing a more consistent mould using recycled plastics. The aim was to perfect a system that would always produce identical weights at a more frequent rate.&lt;/p&gt;






&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Drying Rack Innovation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We repurposed discarded wooden planks to build a drying rack. This allowed us to cure multiple weights simultaneously and improve our workflow.&lt;/p&gt;







